{{afc comment|1=unclear how to do the title[[User:Immanuelle|Immanuelle]] ([[User talk:Immanuelle|talk]]) 23:43, 31 March 2025 (UTC)}}
'''Omi (Omi/Momi) clan''' (小見, 麻績) is one of the clans of Japan.
== Hei Clan Omi == The Omi clan ('''Komi clan''') originating from {{ill|Omi-go, Katori District|ja|小見郷|12=draft}} in {{ill|Shimōsa Province|ja|下総国|12=draft}} (present-day {{ill|Katori, Chiba|ja|香取市|12=draft}}, Chiba Prefecture) belonged to the {{ill|Bōsō Taira|ja|房総平氏|12=draft}} lineage. Several branches emerged: * The {{ill|Sōsa Party Omi|ja|匝瑳氏|12=draft}} clan, stemming from the {{ill|Kazusa clan|ja|上総氏|12=draft}}. * The lineage of {{ill|Chiba Tsunetane|ja|千葉常胤|12=draft}}’s younger brother {{ill|Omi Tanechika|ja|小見胤隆|12=draft}}. * The lineage of {{ill|Shiina Tademitsu|ja|椎名胤光|12=draft}}’s son {{ill|Omi Tanesumi|ja|小見胤澄|12=draft}}. * The lineage of {{ill|Higashi Tadakazu|ja|東胤頼|12=draft}}’s grandson {{ill|Omi Tanechika|ja|小見胤直|12=draft}}.
After the {{ill|Kamakura period|ja|鎌倉時代|12=draft}}, the Omi clan remained historically significant under the {{ill|Chiba clan|ja|千葉氏|12=draft}}.
== Minamoto Clan Momi == The '''Momi clan''' (Omi clan) were local lords of {{ill|Momi-gō, Chikuma District|ja|麻績郷|12=draft}} in {{ill|Shinano Province|ja|信濃国|12=draft}} (present-day {{ill|Omi Village, Nagano|ja|麻績村|12=draft}}, Nagano Prefecture). Their origins date back to the {{ill|Kamakura period|ja|鎌倉時代|12=draft}}, when {{ill|Ogasawara Nagachika|ja|小笠原長親|12=draft}} became the estate steward of Momi and adopted the Momi name. The clan was a branch of the {{ill|Ogasawara clan|ja|小笠原氏|12=draft}}, sharing ancestry with the {{ill|Awa Ogasawara clan|ja|阿波小笠原氏|12=draft}} and the {{ill|Iwami Ogasawara clan|ja|石見小笠原氏|12=draft}}.
This connection is noted in the "Chūkō Buke Keizu": :"Momi, Minamoto clan, based in Shinano. Descended from Ogasawara Awa-no-Kami Nagafusa's son, Shirō Nagachika."
One member of the Momi clan became a concubine of {{ill|Suwa Yorishige|ja|諏訪頼重|12=draft}} and the grandmother of {{ill|Takeda Katsuyori|ja|武田勝頼|12=draft}}.
During the {{ill|Sengoku period|ja|戦国時代 (日本)|12=draft}}, the Momi clan declined due to {{ill|Takeda Shingen|ja|Takeda Shingen|12=draft}}’s invasion of Shinano. {{ill|Aoyagi clan|ja|青柳氏|12=draft}} leader {{ill|Aoyagi Kiyonaga|ja|青柳清長|12=draft}} was granted the Momi name by Shingen and became known as {{ill|Momi Kiyonaga|ja|麻績清長|12=draft}}, taking residence in {{ill|Momi Castle|ja|麻績城|12=draft}} ({{ill|Momi Aoyagi clan|ja|麻績青柳氏|12=draft}}). During this period, the Momi clan served the Takeda with military contributions of 10 horsemen.
The {{ill|Ikushima Tarushima Shrine|ja|生島足島神社|12=draft}} archives contain oaths signed by Takeda vassals, including two from Momi Kiyoshige, showing a focus on maintaining enmity towards neighboring former {{ill|Murakami clan|ja|村上氏|12=draft}} vassals such as the {{ill|Yashiro clan|ja|屋代氏|12=draft}} and {{ill|Muroga clan|ja|室賀氏|12=draft}}.
After the fall of the Takeda in 1582 during the {{ill|Campaign against the Takeda|ja|甲州征伐|12=draft}}, the clan persisted. The head of the Momi clan, {{ill|Aoyagi Yoshinaga|ja|頼長|12=draft}}, served {{ill|Uesugi Kagekatsu|ja|上杉景勝|12=draft}} and later {{ill|Ogasawara Sadayoshi|ja|小笠原貞慶|12=draft}}. However, in 1587, Yoshinaga and his son {{ill|Momi Nagamichi|ja|麻績長迪|12=draft}} were executed, leading to the end of the clan.
== Fujiwara Clan Omi == Another Omi clan claimed descent from the {{ill|Sano clan (Fujiwara)|ja|佐野氏|12=draft}}, a branch of the {{ill|Fujiwara clan|ja|藤原氏|12=draft}} originating from {{ill|Fujiwara Hidesato|ja|Fujiwara no Hidesato|12=draft}}. This branch arose during the late {{ill|Sengoku period|ja|戦国時代 (日本)|12=draft}} when {{ill|Sano Koretsuna|ja|佐野是綱|12=draft}}, a brother of {{ill|Sano Shigetaka|ja|佐野秀綱|12=draft}}, settled in {{ill|Omi-gō, Ashigaru District|ja|麻績郷|12=draft}} (present-day {{ill|Sano, Tochigi|ja|佐野市|12=draft}}, Tochigi Prefecture) and adopted the name {{ill|Omi Koretsuna|ja|小見是綱|12=draft}}.
Additionally, an Omi clan from {{ill|Omi village, Musashi Province|ja|小見邑|12=draft}} (present-day {{ill|Gyōda, Saitama|ja|行田市|12=draft}}, Saitama Prefecture) shares lineage with this family.
